Theoretical analysis - proof sketch

In this section, we provide the proof sketch of our results in Section 3. For simplicity, we present the theoretical analysis for rank one matrix factorization where \(\bm{U}\in\mathbb{R}^{m\times 1}\) and \(\bm{V}\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times 1}\). More detailed proofs for the main theorems are provided in the supplementary material.

### Convergence of ScaledGD

It can be deduced that the objective function of problem (1) is upper bounded by four terms as

\[\|\bm{U}_{k+1}\bm{V}_{k+1}^{\top}-\bm{M}\|_{F} \leq\underbrace{(1-\eta)^{2}\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}-\bm{M} \|_{F}}_{\mbox{1}}+(1-\eta)\eta\underbrace{\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\|\mathcal{V}_{* \perp}^{\top}\mathcal{V}_{k}\|_{2}}_{\mbox{2}}\] \[+\eta(1-\eta)\underbrace{\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\|\mathcal{U}_{*\perp}^{ \top}\mathcal{U}_{k}\|_{2}}_{\mbox{3}}+\eta^{2}\underbrace{\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\left| 1-\frac{\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{\text{u}}\text{cos}\bm{ \theta}_{k}^{\text{v}}}{\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F}}\right|}_{\mbox{ 4}}\] (16)

where \(\mathcal{U}_{k}\) and \(\mathcal{V}_{k}\) correspond to the orthogonal basis of the column space of \(\bm{U}_{k}\) and \(\bm{V}_{k}\), \(\mathcal{U}_{*\perp}\) and \(\mathcal{V}_{*\perp}\) are the orthogonal complements of the left and right singular vector matrices of \(\bm{M}\) (i.e. \(\bm{U}_{*}\), \(\bm{V}_{*}\)), and \(\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{\text{u}}\) is cosine value of the angle between the vectors \(\bm{U}_{k}\) and \(\bm{U}_{*}\), \(\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{\text{v}}\) is cosine value of the angle between the vectors \(\bm{V}_{k}\) and \(\bm{V}_{*}\). The upper-bound depicts the differences between \(\bm{U}_{k+1}\bm{V}_{k+1}^{\top}\) and \(\bm{M}\) in two aspects

* The angle between the subspace of \(\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\) and \(\bm{M}\): \(\|\mathcal{U}_{*\perp}^{\top}\mathcal{U}_{k}\|_{2}\), \(\|\mathcal{V}_{*\perp}^{\top}\mathcal{V}_{k}\|_{2}\);
* The difference of the length (norm) between \(\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\) and \(\bm{M}\): \(\|\bm{M}\|_{F}-\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F}\).

The term 2 and 3 are related to the angle between the subspace of \(\bm{M}\) and \(\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\), the term 4 is related to the difference between the norm of \(\bm{M}\) and \(\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\), as given by the following lemma.

**Lemma 1**.: _If \(\left\langle\bm{M},\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\right\rangle\geq\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm {V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F}^{2}\), then there is constant \(C_{u}\geq 0\) such that_

\[\left|1-\frac{\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{\text{u}}\text{cos}\bm {\theta}_{k}^{\text{v}}}{\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F}}\right|\leq C_{u }\left(\|\bm{M}\|_{F}-\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F}\right)\] (17)

According to Eq. (16), we know that the decrease of the objective function in problem (1) is decided by the decrease of the distance between the subspace (2 and 3) and the difference between the norm of \(\bm{M}\) and \(\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\) (4). The following lemma further reveals that the distance between the subspace of \(\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\) and \(\bm{M}\) decreases.

**Lemma 2**.: (Convergence of the distance between subspaces) _For the ScaledGD (2), if \(\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{\text{u}}\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{ \text{v}}\geq\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F}\), then the following holds_

\[\|\mathcal{U}_{*\perp}^{\top}\mathcal{U}_{k+1}\|_{2}\leq(1-\eta)\|\mathcal{U}_ {*\perp}^{\top}\mathcal{U}_{k}\|_{2},\ \ \|\mathcal{V}_{*\perp}^{\top}\mathcal{V}_{k+1}\|_{2}\leq(1-\eta)\|\mathcal{V}_{* \perp}^{\top}\mathcal{V}_{k}\|_{2}\] (18)

The Lemma 2 indicates that the term 2 and 3 in Eq. (16) decrease linearly if the norm of \(\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F}\) is smaller than norm of the projection of \(\bm{M}\) onto the column and row spaces of \(\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\). At the mean time, the condition \(\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{\text{u}}\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{ \text{v}}\geq\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F}\) also guarantees the linear convergence of the differences between the norm of \(\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\) and \(\bm{M}\).

**Theorem 5**.: (Convergence of the matrix norm) _For the ScaledGD (2), if \(\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{\text{u}}\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{ \text{v}}\geq\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F}\) for all \(k\geq 0\), then we have_

\[\|\bm{M}\|_{F}-\|\bm{U}_{k+1}\bm{V}_{k+1}^{\top}\|_{F}\leq(1-\eta)^{2k}kC_{\alpha}\] (19)

_where \(C_{\alpha}\) is a constant and \(\eta\) is the step length \(0\leq\eta<1\)._

Both Lemma 2 and Theorem 5 are built on the condition that \(\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{\text{u}}\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{ \text{v}}\geq\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F}\) for all \(k\geq 0\), while this is not a trivial condition for ScaledGD. The following lemma guarantees that the condition can be satisfied if the step length \(\eta\) is smaller than a constant.

**Lemma 3**.: _Let \(\eta\leq c_{\eta}<1\) with \(c_{\eta}\) a small constant, if \(\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{0}^{\text{u}}\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{0}^{ \text{v}}\geq\|\bm{U}_{0}\bm{V}_{0}^{\top}\|_{F}\) then the following is true_

\[\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{\text{u}}\text{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{ \text{v}}\geq\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F},\forall k>0.\] (20)The above results guarantee the local linear convergence of the term 2, 3 and 4 on the condition that

\[\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{0}^{u}\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{0}^{v} \geq\|\bm{U}_{0}\bm{V}_{0}^{\top}\|_{F}\] (21)

which is critical for our analysis on random Gaussian initialization and small initialization.

#### 4.1.1 Small initialization

In practice, the condition \(\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{0}^{u}\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{0}^{v} \geq\|\bm{U}_{0}\bm{V}_{0}^{\top}\|_{F}\) can be easily satisfied by very small (near zero) initialization. According to the random matrix theory Theorem 2.7.5 in Tao (2012), for Gaussian initialization there exists \(\nu>0\) such that with high probability \(\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{0}^{u}\) and \(\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{0}^{v}\) is lower bounded by constant \(1/\nu\), therefore one can simply set the norm of \(\bm{U}_{0}\) and \(\bm{V}_{0}\) to be sufficiently small such that the inequality (21) holds. In consequence small initialization can guarantee the global linear convergence of ScaledGD, as shown in Fig. 3. While small initialization is very special. it can not helps us fully understand the global convergence property of ScaledGD from arbitrary initialization for the non-convex objective (1), even though small initialization has been widely used in the global convergence analysis of gradient descent algorithms Stoger and Soltanolkotabi (2021); Ye and Du (2021); Ma and Fattahi (2022) and ScaledGD for symmetric low rank matrix recovery problems Xu et al. (2023); Zhang et al. (2021).

#### 4.1.2 General random initialization

In order to understand the optimization path of ScaledGD for the non-convex objective (1), we present the theoretical analysis of ScaledGD from random Gaussian initialization that may not satisfy the condition in Eq. (21). As shown in Fig. 3, when initialized with \(\sigma=1\) ScaledGD iterations are also attracted by the saddle point thus enter the saddle region (zoomed region marked by red rectangle), while it can escape saddle region very fast. To rigorously characterize the saddle avoid phase, we first show and prove that the norm of matrices \(\bm{U}_{k}\) and \(\bm{V}_{k}\) decrease if \(\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\max\{\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{u},\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{ k}^{v}\}<\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F}\) as given by the following lemma and shown in Fig. 4.

**Lemma 4**.: _If the condition \(\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\max\{\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{u},\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{ k}^{v}\}<\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F}\) is satisfied then we have_

\[\|\bm{U}_{k+1}\|_{F}<\|\bm{U}_{k}\|_{F}\quad\mathrm{and}\quad\|\bm{V}_{k+1}\|_ {F}<\|\bm{V}_{k}\|_{F}.\] (22)

_Furthermore, if the condition \(\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{u}\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{v} \geq\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F}\) is satisfied then we have_

\[\|\bm{U}_{k+1}\|_{F}\geq\|\bm{U}_{k}\|_{F}\quad\mathrm{and}\quad\|\bm{V}_{k+1 }\|_{F}\geq\|\bm{V}_{k}\|_{F}.\] (23)

In general, if we initialize the matrices \(\bm{U}\) and \(\bm{V}\) as \(\mathcal{N}(0,\sigma)\) with large \(\sigma\), then in the initial phase, with high probability we have \(\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\max\{\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{0}^{u},\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{ 0}^{v}\}<\|\bm{U}_{0}\bm{V}_{0}^{\top}\|_{F}\). According to Lemma 3 and Lemma 4, we know that the norm of the matrices \(\bm{U}_{k}\) and \(\bm{V}_{k}\) decreases with the increase of \(k\) until it reaches the condition \(\|\bm{M}\|_{F}\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{u}\mathrm{cos}\bm{\theta}_{k}^{v} \geq\|\bm{U}_{k}\bm{V}_{k}^{\top}\|_{F}\), which is also illustrated in Fig. 4. In Fig. 4, we plot the changes of the norm of matrices \(\bm{U}\) and \(\bm{V}\), the nested subfigure illustrates the the matrix norm in log scale. It is very interesting to study the changes of the matrix norm with respect to the optimization path. Generally, if \(\|\bm{U}_{0}\|_{F}\) and \(\|\bm{V}_{0}\|_{F}\) is initialized very large, then the decrease of the norm will decrease the objective function (1). Meanwhile, \(\bm{U}=\bm{0}\) and \(\bm{V}=\bm{0}\) is a saddle point of the objective function (1), the results in Lemma 4 thus indicate that the matrices \(\bm{U}_{k}\) and \(\bm{V}_{k}\) are updated toward the saddle point zero. While interestingly, as shown in Fig. 4 the matrix norm decreases to a magnitude which is strictly larger than zero, then the matrix norm begins to increase. These observation indicates that ScaledGD can escape from the saddle point zero, the saddle avoid phase is also illustrated in Fig. 5.

